    EDMA form matrix

    Peter Solymos

    edma02-form.Rmd

    The nonparametric estimator gives the mean form matrix (\(\hat{M}\)) and \(\hat{\Sigma}_{K}^\ast\), that we can extract from the fitted model object fit using the Meanform and SigmaKstar functions:

    library(EDMAinR)
#> EDMAinR 0.1-3     2020-06-12
file <- system.file("extdata/crouzon/Crouzon_P0_Global_MUT.xyz", 
    package="EDMAinR")
x <- read_xyz(file)

fit <- edma_fit(x, B=9)
fit
#> EDMA nonparametric fit: Crouzon P0 MUT
#> Call: edma_fit(x = x, B = 9)
#> 3 dimensions, 47 landmarks, 28 replicates, 9 bootstrap runs

str(Meanform(fit))
#>  num [1:47, 1:3] -0.734 -4.238 0.566 2.778 1.99 ...
#>  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
#>   ..$ : chr [1:47] "amsph" "bas" "cpsh" "ethma" ...
#>   ..$ : chr [1:3] "X" "Y" "Z"
str(SigmaKstar(fit))
#>  num [1:47, 1:47] 0.000861 0.001503 -0.001211 -0.003159 -0.000769 ...
#>  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
#>   ..$ : chr [1:47] "amsph" "bas" "cpsh" "ethma" ...
#>   ..$ : chr [1:47] "amsph" "bas" "cpsh" "ethma" ...

    The B argument determines the number of bootstrap resamples to use (resampling specimens with replacement, keeping size \(n\) the same).

    We can extract stacked Euclidean distances (the stacked form matrix \(FM\)) with the get_fm function. The functions allows to sort the table based on decreasing or increasing order by distance:

    head(get_fm(fit))
#>     row   col     dist    lower    upper
#> 1   bas amsph 3.578034 3.544242 3.593131
#> 2  cpsh amsph 1.540182 1.516926 1.547738
#> 3 ethma amsph 3.582046 3.532734 3.594616
#> 4 ethmp amsph 2.836571 2.809799 2.843892
#> 5 laalf amsph 4.422791 4.365103 4.438159
#> 6 lasph amsph 1.703174 1.692026 1.706379
head(get_fm(fit, sort=TRUE, decreasing=TRUE))
#>       row   col     dist    lower    upper
#> 357   opi lnsla 10.52025 10.43218 10.57476
#> 855 rnsla   opi 10.51311 10.43850 10.56415
#> 364  rocc lnsla 10.50312 10.40975 10.56463
#> 435 rnsla  locc 10.50241 10.42781 10.54734
#> 342  locc lnsla 10.48147 10.39466 10.52857
#> 947  rocc rnsla 10.47052 10.39050 10.52732
head(get_fm(fit, sort=TRUE, decreasing=FALSE))
#>       row   col      dist     lower     upper
#> 400 rnslp lnslp 0.1437961 0.1397424 0.1495540
#> 362 rnsla lnsla 0.2240884 0.2180449 0.2364678
#> 416  loci  locc 0.5006732 0.4911632 0.5183575
#> 977  roci  rocc 0.5034007 0.4838632 0.5265220
#> 127  rpsh  cpsh 0.5263067 0.5117256 0.5335533
#> 105  lpsh  cpsh 0.5751019 0.5637977 0.5837257

    The 2D plot gives the projection of the mean form using multidimensional scaling (it uses \(FM\) based on \(\hat{M}\)) dot size proportional to SigmaKstar(fit) diagonal elements (scaling can be scaled by the cex argument):

    plot_2d(fit)

    library(rgl)
plot_3d(fit, col=4)
decorate3d()
rglwidget(width = 600, height = 600, reuse = FALSE)

    See ?rgl::plot3d for options to modify the 3D plot.
